{"title_page": "Rosemary Harris", "text_new": "{{About|the English actress|the author of children's fiction|Rosemary Harris (writer)}}\n{{short description|English actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Rosemary Harris Spiderman 2007 Shankbone.jpg\n| caption = Harris at the 2007 ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' premiere in [[Queens, New York]]\n| birth_name = Rosemary Ann Harris\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|9|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Ashby-de-la-Zouch]], [[Leicestershire]], United Kingdom\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Ellis Rabb]]|1959|1967|reason=divorce}}<br />{{marriage|[[John Ehle]]|1967|2018|reason=died}}\n| yearsactive = 1948&ndash;present\n| occupation = Actress\n| children = [[Jennifer Ehle]]\n}}\n\n'''Rosemary Ann Harris''' (born 19 September 1927) is an English actress. She is a 1986 [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] inductee.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html Rosemary Harris Film Reference bio]. Filmreference.com. Retrieved on 27 August 2011.</ref>\n\nHarris began her stage career in 1948, before making her [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] debut in 1952. For her New York stage work, she is a four-time [[Drama Desk Award]] winner and nine-time [[Tony Award]] nominee, winning the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play]] in 1966 for ''[[The Lion in Winter]]''. On television, she won an [[Emmy Award]] for the 1974 TV serial ''[[Notorious Woman]]'', and a [[Golden Globe Award]] for the 1978 miniseries ''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]''. For the 1994 film ''[[Tom & Viv]]'', she received a [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination. She is the mother of actress [[Jennifer Ehle]]. In 2002, she portrayed [[Peter Parker]]\u2019s [[Aunt May]] in [[Sam Raimi]]\u2019s ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'', a role she reprised in 2004's ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' and 2007's ''[[Spider-Man 3]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHarris was born in [[Ashby-de-la-Zouch]], [[Leicestershire]], the daughter of Enid Maude Frances (n\u00e9e Campion) and Stafford Berkely Harris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1919/1919%20-%201083.html|title=anti-aircraft corps &#124; august &#124; smyth pigott &#124; 1919 &#124; 1083 &#124; Flight Archive<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rosemary Harris |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023605/bio |accessdate=4 August 2018 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511132317/https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023605/bio |archivedate=11 May 2006}}</ref> One of her grandmothers was from the German enclave in Kronstadt, Transylvania in the Austrian Empire.<ref name=\"harris1\">[http://www.nmia.com/~paulos/rosemary.html Rosemary Harris and the Picture: Madonna of the Slaughtered Jews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215182541/http://www.nmia.com/~paulos/rosemary.html |date=15 February 2006 }}. Nmia.com. Retrieved on 27 August 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.eroiiromanieichic.ro/?p=307 Hollywood made in Romania (partea a II-a)]. eroiiromanieichic.ro (8 December). Retrieved on 13 January 2013.</ref> Her father was in the [[Royal Air Force]] and as a result, Harris' family lived in [[British India|India]] during her childhood.<ref>{{cite news |title=Interview with Actor Rosemary Harris |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Interview-with-Actor-Rosemary-Harris-20140909 |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=Broadway World |date=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost1986\">{{cite news |last1=Rosenfeld |first1=Megan |title=Rosemary Harris, Blissfully |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1986/03/30/rosemary-harris-blissfully/5fc6dce3-a0de-40d7-98dd-f4d9636da080/ |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=30 March 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Welsh |first1=Anne Marie |title=Six decades on, Rosemary Harris' career is still in the 'Pink' |url=http://legacy.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20070929/news_lz1c29harris.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=29 September 2007}}</ref> She attended [[convent school]]s, and later studied at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] from 1951 to 1952.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|title=American Theatre: A Chronicle of Comedy and Drama, 1969\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IUxnDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA96|year=2001|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-512347-0|page=96}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gussow|first1=Mel|title=For Rosemary Harris, A Delicate Balance Of Her Art and Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/27/theater/for-rosemary-harris-a-delicate-balance-of-her-art-and-life.html|accessdate=5 November 2017|work=The New York Times|date=27 May 1996}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in her acting career, she gained experience in English [[repertory]] theatre. In 1948, she acted in ''Kiss and Tell'' at [[Eastbourne]] with Tilsa Page and [[John Clark (actor/director)|John Clark]] and later with Anthony Cundell's company at Penzance, where she played the mother in ''Black Chiffon''. She went from Penzance to train at [[RADA]].<ref name=\"Deadline2015\">{{cite news |last1=Gerard |first1=Jeremy |title=Rosemary Harris On \u2018The Holocaust\u2019, Tom Stoppard & Liz Taylor: Conversations With Jeremy Gerard |url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/rosemary-harris-holocaust-tom-stoppard-spider-man-1201339810/ |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=27 January 2015}}</ref> She first appeared in [[New York City|New York]] in 1951 in [[Moss Hart]]'s ''Climate of Eden'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bordman|first1=Gerald|last2=Hischak|first2=Thomas S.|title=The Oxford Companion to American Theatre|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000bord|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-516986-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000bord/page/293 293]}}</ref> and then returned to Britain for her West End debut in ''The Seven Year Itch'' which ran for a year at the Aldwich.\n\n[[File:Rosemary Harris actress 1962.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Harris at the Chichester Festival Theatre, 1962]]\n\nHarris then entered a classical acting period in productions with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] and then the [[Old Vic]], appearing at the latter as [[Ophelia]] in the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre Company]]'s opening production of ''Hamlet'' in October 1963, alongside [[Peter O'Toole]] in the title role.<ref name=\"BBC Online 22 October 2013\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24620781|title= National Theatre actress: 'I wasn't a bit nervous'|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 October 2013|website= [[BBC Online]] |publisher= | accessdate= 9 June 2016 }}</ref> Writing in UK newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2003 as part of a series on landmark theatre productions, playwright [[Samantha Ellis]] noted  of the National Theatre's opening night: {{quote|Olivier gloomily anticipated bad reviews. But RB Marriott, in ''The Stage'', found O'Toole to be \"a magnificent Prince\" and Rosemary Harris \"the most real and touching Ophelia\". (In contrast, Felix Barker, in the ''Evening News'', called her \"an embarrassing deb who has had too much gin\".) And Harold Hobson, in ''The Sunday Times'', was overcome.<ref name=\"Guardian 12 March 2003\">{{cite news |last= Ellis |first= Samantha |title= Hamlet, National Theatre, October 1963 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2003/mar/12/theatre.artsfeatures1| date= 12 March 2003|newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |location=London| accessdate=9 June 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nHer first film followed, ''[[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|Beau Brummell]]'' (1954) with [[Stewart Granger]] and [[Elizabeth Taylor]],<ref name=\"Deadline2015\"/> and then a touring season with the Old Vic brought her back to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in [[Tyrone Guthrie]]'s production of ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]''. She met [[Ellis Rabb]] who had plans to start his own producing company on Broadway. By 1959, the ''Association of Producing Artist'' (APA) was established, and she and Rabb were married on 4 December of that year.<ref name=encyc>{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/harris-rosemary-1927|title=Harris, Rosemary 1927(?)-|website=encyclopedia.com|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214005259/https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/harris-rosemary-1927|archive-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref><ref name=filmref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html|title=Rosemary Harris Biography (1930?-)|website=filmreference.com|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629235755/http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html|archive-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, she returned to Britain and [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] during its opening season when the director was [[Laurence Olivier]]; she appeared as Elena in Olivier's celebrated 1962\u201363 Chichester production of ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''.<ref>See the VHS recording of this performance issued by Arthur Cantor Films, New York.</ref> In 1964, she was Ophelia to [[Peter O'Toole|Peter O'Toole's]] ''[[Hamlet]]'' in the inaugural production of the [[Royal National Theatre]] of Great Britain. {{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nReturning to New York, she worked further with the APA, and then was cast as [[Eleanor of Aquitaine]] in ''[[The Lion in Winter]]'', a performance that garnered her a [[Tony Award]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reich |first1=Ronni |title=Rosemary Harris returns to the New York stage |url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/02/rosemary_harris_returns_to_the_new_york_stage.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |publisher=[[NJ.com]] |date=25 February 2014}}</ref> Rabb directed her one last time as Natasha in ''[[War and Peace]]'' in 1967, the same year they agreed to divorce.<ref name=encyc/><ref name=filmref/> A little while later, Harris married the American writer [[John Ehle]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sandomir |first1=Richard |title=John Ehle, Who Rooted His Novels in Appalachia, Is Dead at 92 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/obituaries/john-ehle-who-rooted-novels-in-appalachia-is-dead-at-92.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=12 April 2018}}</ref> They settled in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], [[North Carolina]],<ref name=\"WashingtonPost1986\"/>  where their daughter, Jennifer, was born in 1969. [[Jennifer Ehle]] followed in her mother's footsteps by becoming a noted film, television and Broadway actress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kavanagh |first1=Julie |last2=Avedon |first2=Richard |title=Chameleons |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1996/05/13/chameleons |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=13 May 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Harris starred in the BBC TV serial ''[[Notorious Woman]]'', which aired on [[PBS]] in the US as part of [[Masterpiece Theatre]]. For this role, she won the 1976 [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series]]. She won a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Television Series - Drama|Best Actress \u2013 TV Drama]] for the 1978 [[NBC]] miniseries ''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]'', which also starred [[Meryl Streep]]. Reviewing the BBC's 1983 production of ''[[To the Lighthouse (film)|To the Lighthouse]]'', an adaptation of [[Virginia Woolf]]'s [[To the Lighthouse|novel of the same name]], ''[[The New York Times]]''' John J. O'Connor wrote: \"A luminous, flawless performance by Miss Harris makes Mrs. Ramsay as memorable on film as she is on the printed page.\"<ref name=\"New York Times 12 October 1984\">{{cite news |last= O'Connor |first= John J.|title= TV Weekend; Virginia Woolf's 'To the Lighthouse'|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/12/arts/tv-weekend-virginia-woolf-s-to-the-lighthouse.html| date= 12 October 1984|newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |location=New York City| accessdate= 9 June 2016 }}</ref> She received a [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] [[Academy Award|Oscar]] nomination for the 1994 film ''[[Tom & Viv]]''. Harris and her daughter Ehle, played the young and elderly incarnations, respectively, of the same character in [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]]'s 1999 film ''[[Sunshine (1999 film)|Sunshine]]'', about a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] Jewish family. They had previously played the young and old Calypso in the [[Channel 4]] production of ''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]'' (1992).\n\nHarris appeared in the rotating cast of the Off-Broadway staged reading of ''[[Wit & Wisdom]]''.<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/shows/wit-and-wisdom_20415/ \"Synopsis of Wit & Wisdom\"] at Theater Mania</ref> In 2007, she received the [[North Carolina Award]] for fine arts. Her husband, John Ehle, won the same award in 1972 for literature.<ref>[http://statelibrary.dcr.state.nc.us/ncawards/nca2.asp?bn=rhehle North Carolina Award profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815185943/http://statelibrary.dcr.state.nc.us/ncawards/nca2.asp?bn=rhehle |date=15 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, she appeared as [[Aunt May|Aunt May Parker]] in the [[Spider-Man (2002 film)|first film adaptation of ''Spider-Man'']], reprising the role in the sequels ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' (2004) and ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' (2007).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salfino |first1=Michael |title=Hold On, You\u2019re Spider-Man\u2019s Aunt May? |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spider-mans-aunt-may-has-never-looked-younger-1498667227 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=4 August 2018 |date=28 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Monahan |first1=Mark |title=The face is familiar: Rosemary Harris |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3670713/The-face-is-familiar-Rosemary-Harris.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2018, a week before her 91st birthday, Harris took over the role of Mrs Higgins in [[My Fair Lady#2018 Broadway revival|the Broadway revival of ''My Fair Lady'']] from [[Diana Rigg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/first-look-at-tony-winner-rosemary-harris-in-my-fair-lady-on-broadway|title=First Look at Tony Winner Rosemary Harris in My Fair Lady on Broadway|first=Hannah|last=Vine|date=28 September 2018|website=Playbill|accessdate=14 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085106/http://www.playbill.com/article/first-look-at-tony-winner-rosemary-harris-in-my-fair-lady-on-broadway|archive-date=16 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/news-features/rosemary-harris-returns-to-broadway-in-my-fair-lady-at-lincoln-center-theater|title=Rosemary Harris returns to Broadway in My Fair Lady at Lincoln Center Theater|website=New York Theater Guide|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1954\n|''[[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|Beau Brummell]]''\n|Mrs. Fitzherbert\n|film debut\n|-\n|1957\n|''[[The Shiralee (1957 film)|The Shiralee]]''\n|Lily Parker\n|\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Uncle Vanya (1963 film)|Uncle Vanya]]''\n|Yelena\n|\n|-\n|1968\n|''[[A Flea in Her Ear (film)|A Flea in Her Ear]]''\n|Gabrielle Chandebisse\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[The Boys from Brazil (film)|The Boys from Brazil]]''\n|Mrs. Doring\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[The Ploughman's Lunch]]''\n|Ann Barrington\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Crossing Delancey]]''\n|Pauline Swift\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[The Delinquents (1989 film)|The Delinquents]]''\n|Isobel\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[The Bridge (1992 film)|The Bridge]]''\n|Aunt Jude\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Tom & Viv]]''\n|Rose Haigh-Wood\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Hamlet (1996 film)|Hamlet]]''\n|Player Queen\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[My Life So Far]]''\n|Gamma\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Sunshine (1999 film)|Sunshine]]''\n|Valerie Sors\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Gift (2000 film)|The Gift]]''\n|Annie's Granny\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Blow Dry]]''\n|Daisy\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Aunt May|Aunt May Parker]]\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Spider-Man 2]]''\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Being Julia]]''\n|Julia's mother\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Spider-Man 3]]''\n|Aunt May Parker\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Before the Devil Knows You're Dead]]''\n|Nanette\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Is Anybody There?]]''\n|Elsie\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''The Monday Before Thanksgiving''\n|Lillian Cotlo\n|Short film\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Radio Free Albemuth (film)|Radio Free Ablemuth]]''\n|VALIS (voice role)\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[This Means War (film)|This Means War]]''\n|Nana Foster\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The von Trapp Family: A Life of Music]]''\n|Older Agathe von Trapp\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1952\n|''A Cradle of Wlllow''\n|Tansy Clampett\n|Television debut<br/>Television Movie\n|-\n|1952\n|''[[Studio One (U.S. TV series)|Studio One in Hollywood]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"The Great Lady\"\n|-\n|1955\n|''[[Othello (1955 film)|Othello]]''\n|[[Desdemona]]\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1957\n|''Twelfth Night''\n|Viola\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Suspicion (TV series)|Suspicion]]''\n|Sybil Merton\n|Episode: \"Lord Arthur Savile's Crime\"\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Omnibus (U.S. TV series)|Omnibus]]''\n|Cordelia\n|Episode: \"Moment of Truth\"\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Dial M for Murder!|Dial M for Murder]]''\n|Margot Wendice\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1958\n|''Folio''\n|Dynamene\n|Episode: \"A Phoenix Too Frequent\"\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[DuPont Show of the Month]]'' \n|Cathy Linton\n|Episode: Wuthering Heights \n|-\n|1959\n|''[[Encounter (1958 TV series)|Encounter]]''\n|Norah Marsh\n|Episode: \"The Land of Promise\"\n|-\n|1964\n|''[[Profiles in Courage (TV series)|Profiles in Courage]]''\n|Mary S. McDowell\n|Episode: \"Mary S. McDowell\"\n|-\n|1966\n|''Blithe Spirit''\n|Elvira Condomine\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[Uncle Vanya (1963 film)|Uncle Vanya]]''\n|Jelena Andrejewna\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Notorious Woman]]''\n|George Sand\n|Television Miniseries; 7 episodes\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[The Royal Family (film)|The Royal Family]]''\n|Julie Cavendish\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]''\n|Berta Palitz Weiss\n|Television Miniseries; 4 episodes\n|-\n|1979\u201380\n|''[[The Chisholms]]''\n|Minerva Chisholm\n|Television Miniseries; 13 episodes\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[To the Lighthouse (film)|To the Lighthouse]]''\n|Mrs. Ramsay\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]''\n|Calypso (older)\n|Television Miniseries; 2 episodes\n|-\n|1994\n|''Under the Hammer''\n|Hester Bovington\n|Episode: \"The Spectre at the Feast\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Summer Day's Dream]]''\n|Margaret Dawlish\n|One-off production in the BBC's ''Performance'' series \n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Little Riders]]''\n|Grandma Roden\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Death of a Salesman (1996 film)|Death of a Salesman]]''\n|Linda\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|2004\n|''Belonging''\n|May\n|Television Movie\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|Francine Brooks\n|Episode: \"[[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit episodes|Wet]]\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''The Money''\n|Ellen Knox\n|Television Movie\n|}\n\n=== Theatre ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n! Venue \n|-\n|1952\n|''The Climate of Eden''\n|Mabel\n|[[Martin Beck Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1953-54 \n|''The Seven Year Itch''\n|The Girl\n|[[Aldwych Theatre]], London \n|-\n|1954\n|''[[The Crucible]]''\n|Elizabeth Proctor\n|[[Bristol Old Vic]], London \n|-\n|1956\n|''[[Troilus and Cressida]]''\n|Cressida\n|[[Winter Garden Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1957\n|''The Glass Eye''\n|Dorothy Witley\n|[[American National Theater and Academy|ANTA Playhouse]], New York\n|-\n|1958\n|''Interlock''\n|Hilde\n|[[ANTA Playhouse]], New York \n|-\n|1958\n|''The Disenchanted''\n|Jere Halliday\n|[[Eugene O'Neill Theatre|Coronet Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1960\n|''The Tumbler''\n|Lennie\n|[[Helen Hayes Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Uncle Vanya]]''\n|Ilyena \n|[[Chichester Festival Theatre]], London\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Hamlet (play)|Hamlet]]''\n| Ophelia\n| [[Old Vic Theatre]], London \n|-\n|1965\n|''Judith''\n|Judith\n| rowspan=3|[[Phoenix Theatre (New York City)|Phoenix Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|1965\n|''[[Man and Superman]]''\n|Violet Robinson\n|-\n|1965\n|''War and Peace''\n|[[Natasha Rostova]]\n|-\n|1965 \n|''Herakles'' \n|Megara\n|[[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[The Lion in Winter]]''\n|Eleanor\n|[[Ambassador Theatre (New York City)|Ambassador Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1966\u201367\n|''[[The School for Scandal]]''\n|Lady Teazle\n|rowspan=6|[[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[Right You Are (if you think so)|Right You Are If You Think You Are]]''\n|Signora Ponza\n|-\n|1966\n|''We, Comrades Three''\n|Young Woman\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[The Wild Duck]]''\n|Gina\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[You Can't Take It with You (play)|You Can't Take it With You]]''\n|Alice Sycamore\n|-\n|1967\n|''War and Peace''\n|[[Natasha Rostova]]\n|-\n|1971\u201372\n|''[[Old Times]]''\n|Anna\n|[[Nederlander Theatre|Billy Rose Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[The Merchant of Venice]]''\n|Portia\n|rowspan=2|[[Vivian Beaumont Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[A Streetcar Named Desire|A Street Car Named Desire]]''\n|[[Blanche DuBois|Blanche Du Bois]]\n|-\n|1975\u201376\n|''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''\n|Julie Cavendish\n|[[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] <br/> [[Helen Hayes Theatre]], Broadway \n|-\n|1977 || ''The New York Idea'' || Vida Phillimore || rowspan=2|[[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] \n|-\n|1977 || ''[[Three Sisters (play)|The Three Sisters]]'' || Olga\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|rowspan=2|''[[Heartbreak House]]''\n|rowspan=2|Hesione Hushabye\n|[[Circle in the Square Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|[[Royal Shakespeare Company|Theatre Royal]], London \n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Pack of Lies]]''\n|Barbara Jackson\n|[[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre|Royale Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1985\u201386\n|''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]''\n|Judith Bliss\n|[[Music Box Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1991\u201393\n|''[[Lost in Yonkers]]''\n|Grandma Kurnitz\n|[[Richard Rogers Theatre]], Broadway <br/> [[Royal Strand Theatre]], London\n|-\n|1994\u201395\n|''[[An Inspector Calls]]''\n|Sybil Birling\n|[[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre|Royale Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[A Delicate Balance (play)|A Delicate Balance]]''\n|Agnes\n|[[Plymouth Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]''\n|May Davenport\n|[[Walter Kerr Theatre]], Broadway <br/> [[Eugene O'Neill Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[All Over]]''\n|The Wife\n|[[Gramercy Theatre]], New York City\n|-\n|2005 \n|''The Other Side''\n|Levana Julak\n|[[Manhattan Theatre Club]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|2007\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Oscar and the Lady in Pink (novel)|Oscar and the Lady in Pink]]''\n| rowspan= 2|Performer \n|[[Old Globe Theatre]], San Diego \n|-\n|2008\n|Florence Gould Hall, New York City \n|-\n|2009\n|''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''\n|Fanny Cavendish\n|[[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[The Road to Mecca (play)|The Road to Mecca]]''\n|Miss Helen\n|[[American Airlines Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Indian Ink]]''\n|Eleanor Swan\n|[[Roundabout Theatre Company|Laura Pels Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|2018-19\n|''[[My Fair Lady (musical)|My Fair Lady]]''\n|Mrs. Higgins\n|[[Vivian Beaumont Theatre]], Broadway\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Dark Side of the Moon: A Sci-Fi Adventure|Dark Side of the Moon]]''\n|Miner Woman (voice role)\n|[[PC game|PC]] version for [[Windows 9x|Windows 95/98]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n=== Film accolades ===\n'''Academy Award'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Tom & Viv (film)|Tom & Viv]]''\n|[[Academy Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''BAFTA Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[The Ploughman's Lunch]]''\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Gotham Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Before the Devil Knows You're Dead]]''\n|[[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Ensemble Cast|Best Ensemble Cast]]\n|{{WON}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Critics Choice Film Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Before the Devil Knows You're Dead|Before the Devil Know's You're Dead]]''\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Acting Ensemble|Best Acting Ensemble]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n'''National Board of Review'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Tom & Viv]]''\n|[[National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|{{WON}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television accolades ===\n'''Primetime Emmy Award'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Notorious Woman]]''\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Best Lead Actress in a Limited Series]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]''\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Best Lead Actress in a Limited Series]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Golden Globe Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n| 1976\n|''[[Notorious Woman]]''\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Television Series \u2013 Drama]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]''\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Television Series - Drama]]\n|{{win}}\n|}\n\n=== Theatre accolades ===\n'''Tony Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[The Lion in Winter]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{WON}}<ref name=\"TonyAwards\">{{cite news |title=Search Past Tony Award Winners and Nominees |url=https://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/history/pastwinners/tonys_results.html?lname=rosemary+harris |accessdate=4 August 2018 |publisher=[[Tony Awards]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|1972\n|''[[Old Times]]''\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{Nominated}}<ref name=\"TonyAwards\"/>\n|-\n|1976 \n|''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''  \n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Heartbreak House]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Pack of Lies]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1986 \n|''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[A Delicate Balance (play)|A Delicate Balance]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]] \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actress in a Play|Best Featured Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2019\n| \n|[[Special Tony Award|Lifetime Achievement in the Theatre]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Drama Desk Award''' \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1972\n|''[[Old Times]]''\n|Best Performance\n|{{win}}<ref name=\"ibdb.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/rosemary-harris-44269/#awards|title=Rosemary Harris \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff &#124; IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]''\n|Best Performance\n|{{win}}<ref name=\"ibdb.com\"/>\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'' \n|Best Performance\n|{{win}}<ref name=\"ibdb.com\"/>\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[The Royal Family (play)|The Royal Family]]''\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play|Actress in a Play]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Heartbreak House]]''\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play|Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Pack of Lies (play)|Pack of Lies]]''\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play|Actress in a Play]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|1996 \n|''[[A Delicate Balance (play)|A Delicate Balance]]''\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play|Actress in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Laurence Olivier Award'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[All My Sons]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a Revival|Actress in a Revival]] \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Heartbreak House]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a Revival|Actress in a Revival]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Lost in Yonkers]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Supporting Actress]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Obie Award'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Category\n!Results\n|-\n|1962\n| ''[[The Tavern (play)|The Tavern]]'', ''[[The School for Scandal]]'', ''[[The Seagull]]''\n|[[Obie Award for Distinguished Performance by an Actress|Distinguished Performance by an Actress]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|1965\n|''[[Judith (Giraudoux)|Judith]]'', ''[[Man and Superman]]'', ''War and Peace''\n|Distinguished Performance by an Actress\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[All Over]]''\n|[[Obie Award for Distinguished Performance by an Actress|Distinguished Performance by an Actress]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{IMDb name|365281}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{iobdb name|10511}}\n*[http://www.rosemaryharris.net Presenting Rosemary Harris website]: articles and images\n*[https://soundcloud.com/american-theatre-wing/episode-242 Rosemary Harris] \u2013 ''Downstage Center'' interview at [[American Theatre Wing|American Theatre Wing.org]]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Rosemary Harris\n|list =\n{{DramaDesk PlayOutstandingActress 1975-2000}}\n{{Distinguished Performance Award}}\n{{EmmyAward MiniseriesLeadActress 1976-2000}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActressTVDrama 1969-1979}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Supporting Actress Motion Picture}}\n{{Special Tony Award}}\n{{TonyAward PlayLeadActress 1947-1975}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar |Film}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Rosemary Ann}}\n[[Category:People from Ashby-de-la-Zouch]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Actress Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Miniseries or Movie Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:British expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n[[Category:English Shakespearean actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the English actress|the author of children's fiction|Rosemary Harris (writer)}}\n{{short description|English actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Rosemary Harris Spiderman 2007 Shankbone.jpg\n| caption = Harris at the 2007 ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' premiere in [[Queens, New York]]\n| birth_name = Rosemary Ann Harris\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|9|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Ashby-de-la-Zouch]], [[Leicestershire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Ellis Rabb]]|1959|1967|reason=divorce}} <br> {{marriage|[[John Ehle]]|1967|2018|reason=died}}\n| yearsactive = 1948&ndash;present\n| occupation = Actress\n| children = [[Jennifer Ehle]]\n}}\n\n'''Rosemary Ann Harris''' (born 19 September 1927) is an English actress. She is a 1986 [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] inductee.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html Rosemary Harris Film Reference bio]. Filmreference.com. Retrieved on 27 August 2011.</ref>\n\nHarris began her stage career in 1948, before making her [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] debut in 1952. For her New York stage work, she is a four-time [[Drama Desk Award]] winner and nine-time [[Tony Award]] nominee, winning the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play]] in 1966 for ''[[The Lion in Winter]]''. On television, she won an [[Emmy Award]] for the 1974 TV serial ''[[Notorious Woman]]'', and a [[Golden Globe Award]] for the 1978 miniseries ''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]''. For the 1994 film ''[[Tom & Viv]]'', she received a [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination. She is the mother of actress [[Jennifer Ehle]]. In 2002, she portrayed [[Peter Parker]]\u2019s [[Aunt May]] in [[Sam Raimi]]\u2019s ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'', a role she reprised in 2004's ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' and 2007's ''[[Spider-Man 3]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHarris was born in [[Ashby-de-la-Zouch]], [[Leicestershire]], the daughter of Enid Maude Frances (n\u00e9e Campion) and Stafford Berkely Harris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1919/1919%20-%201083.html|title=anti-aircraft corps &#124; august &#124; smyth pigott &#124; 1919 &#124; 1083 &#124; Flight Archive<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rosemary Harris |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023605/bio |accessdate=4 August 2018 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511132317/https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023605/bio |archivedate=11 May 2006}}</ref> One of her grandmothers was from the German enclave in Kronstadt, Transylvania in the Austrian Empire.<ref name=\"harris1\">[http://www.nmia.com/~paulos/rosemary.html Rosemary Harris and the Picture: Madonna of the Slaughtered Jews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215182541/http://www.nmia.com/~paulos/rosemary.html |date=15 February 2006 }}. Nmia.com. Retrieved on 27 August 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.eroiiromanieichic.ro/?p=307 Hollywood made in Romania (partea a II-a)]. eroiiromanieichic.ro (8 December). Retrieved on 13 January 2013.</ref> Her father was in the [[Royal Air Force]] and as a result, Harris' family lived in [[British India|India]] during her childhood.<ref>{{cite news |title=Interview with Actor Rosemary Harris |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Interview-with-Actor-Rosemary-Harris-20140909 |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=Broadway World |date=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost1986\">{{cite news |last1=Rosenfeld |first1=Megan |title=Rosemary Harris, Blissfully |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1986/03/30/rosemary-harris-blissfully/5fc6dce3-a0de-40d7-98dd-f4d9636da080/ |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=30 March 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Welsh |first1=Anne Marie |title=Six decades on, Rosemary Harris' career is still in the 'Pink' |url=http://legacy.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20070929/news_lz1c29harris.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=29 September 2007}}</ref> She attended [[convent school]]s, and later studied at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] from 1951 to 1952.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|title=American Theatre: A Chronicle of Comedy and Drama, 1969\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IUxnDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA96|year=2001|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-512347-0|page=96}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gussow|first1=Mel|title=For Rosemary Harris, A Delicate Balance Of Her Art and Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/27/theater/for-rosemary-harris-a-delicate-balance-of-her-art-and-life.html|accessdate=5 November 2017|work=The New York Times|date=27 May 1996}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in her acting career, she gained experience in English [[repertory]] theatre. In 1948, she acted in ''Kiss and Tell'' at [[Eastbourne]] with Tilsa Page and [[John Clark (actor/director)|John Clark]] and later with Anthony Cundell's company at Penzance, where she played the mother in ''Black Chiffon''. She went from Penzance to train at [[RADA]].<ref name=\"Deadline2015\">{{cite news |last1=Gerard |first1=Jeremy |title=Rosemary Harris On \u2018The Holocaust\u2019, Tom Stoppard & Liz Taylor: Conversations With Jeremy Gerard |url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/rosemary-harris-holocaust-tom-stoppard-spider-man-1201339810/ |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=27 January 2015}}</ref> She first appeared in [[New York City|New York]] in 1951 in [[Moss Hart]]'s ''Climate of Eden'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bordman|first1=Gerald|last2=Hischak|first2=Thomas S.|title=The Oxford Companion to American Theatre|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000bord|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-516986-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000bord/page/293 293]}}</ref> and then returned to Britain for her West End debut in ''The Seven Year Itch'' which ran for a year at the Aldwich.\n\n[[File:Rosemary Harris actress 1962.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Harris at the Chichester Festival Theatre, 1962]]\n\nHarris then entered a classical acting period in productions with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] and then the [[Old Vic]], appearing at the latter as [[Ophelia]] in the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre Company]]'s opening production of ''Hamlet'' in October 1963, alongside [[Peter O'Toole]] in the title role.<ref name=\"BBC Online 22 October 2013\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24620781|title= National Theatre actress: 'I wasn't a bit nervous'|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 October 2013|website= [[BBC Online]] |publisher= | accessdate= 9 June 2016 }}</ref> Writing in UK newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2003 as part of a series on landmark theatre productions, playwright [[Samantha Ellis]] noted  of the National Theatre's opening night: {{quote|Olivier gloomily anticipated bad reviews. But RB Marriott, in ''The Stage'', found O'Toole to be \"a magnificent Prince\" and Rosemary Harris \"the most real and touching Ophelia\". (In contrast, Felix Barker, in the ''Evening News'', called her \"an embarrassing deb who has had too much gin\".) And Harold Hobson, in ''The Sunday Times'', was overcome.<ref name=\"Guardian 12 March 2003\">{{cite news |last= Ellis |first= Samantha |title= Hamlet, National Theatre, October 1963 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2003/mar/12/theatre.artsfeatures1| date= 12 March 2003|newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |location=London| accessdate=9 June 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nHer first film followed, ''[[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|Beau Brummell]]'' (1954) with [[Stewart Granger]] and [[Elizabeth Taylor]],<ref name=\"Deadline2015\"/> and then a touring season with the Old Vic brought her back to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in [[Tyrone Guthrie]]'s production of ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]''. She met [[Ellis Rabb]] who had plans to start his own producing company on Broadway. By 1959, the ''Association of Producing Artist'' (APA) was established, and she and Rabb were married on 4 December of that year.<ref name=encyc>{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/harris-rosemary-1927|title=Harris, Rosemary 1927(?)-|website=encyclopedia.com|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214005259/https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/harris-rosemary-1927|archive-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref><ref name=filmref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html|title=Rosemary Harris Biography (1930?-)|website=filmreference.com|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629235755/http://www.filmreference.com/film/89/Rosemary-Harris.html|archive-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, she returned to Britain and [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] during its opening season when the director was [[Laurence Olivier]]; she appeared as Elena in Olivier's celebrated 1962\u201363 Chichester production of ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''.<ref>See the VHS recording of this performance issued by Arthur Cantor Films, New York.</ref> In 1964, she was Ophelia to [[Peter O'Toole|Peter O'Toole's]] ''[[Hamlet]]'' in the inaugural production of the [[Royal National Theatre]] of Great Britain. {{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nReturning to New York, she worked further with the APA, and then was cast as [[Eleanor of Aquitaine]] in ''[[The Lion in Winter]]'', a performance that garnered her a [[Tony Award]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reich |first1=Ronni |title=Rosemary Harris returns to the New York stage |url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/02/rosemary_harris_returns_to_the_new_york_stage.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |publisher=[[NJ.com]] |date=25 February 2014}}</ref> Rabb directed her one last time as Natasha in ''[[War and Peace]]'' in 1967, the same year they agreed to divorce.<ref name=encyc/><ref name=filmref/> A little while later, Harris married the American writer [[John Ehle]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sandomir |first1=Richard |title=John Ehle, Who Rooted His Novels in Appalachia, Is Dead at 92 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/obituaries/john-ehle-who-rooted-novels-in-appalachia-is-dead-at-92.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=12 April 2018}}</ref> They settled in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], [[North Carolina]],<ref name=\"WashingtonPost1986\"/>  where their daughter, Jennifer, was born in 1969. [[Jennifer Ehle]] followed in her mother's footsteps by becoming a noted film, television and Broadway actress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kavanagh |first1=Julie |last2=Avedon |first2=Richard |title=Chameleons |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1996/05/13/chameleons |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=13 May 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Harris starred in the BBC TV serial ''[[Notorious Woman]]'', which aired on [[PBS]] in the US as part of [[Masterpiece Theatre]]. For this role, she won the 1976 [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series]]. She won a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Television Series - Drama|Best Actress \u2013 TV Drama]] for the 1978 [[NBC]] miniseries ''[[Holocaust (miniseries)|Holocaust]]'', which also starred [[Meryl Streep]]. Reviewing the BBC's 1983 production of ''[[To the Lighthouse (film)|To the Lighthouse]]'', an adaptation of [[Virginia Woolf]]'s [[To the Lighthouse|novel of the same name]], ''[[The New York Times]]''' John J. O'Connor wrote: \"A luminous, flawless performance by Miss Harris makes Mrs. Ramsay as memorable on film as she is on the printed page.\"<ref name=\"New York Times 12 October 1984\">{{cite news |last= O'Connor |first= John J.|title= TV Weekend; Virginia Woolf's 'To the Lighthouse'|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/12/arts/tv-weekend-virginia-woolf-s-to-the-lighthouse.html| date= 12 October 1984|newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |location=New York City| accessdate= 9 June 2016 }}</ref> She received a [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] [[Academy Award|Oscar]] nomination for the 1994 film ''[[Tom & Viv]]''. Harris and her daughter Ehle, played the young and elderly incarnations, respectively, of the same character in [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]]'s 1999 film ''[[Sunshine (1999 film)|Sunshine]]'', about a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] Jewish family. They had previously played the young and old Calypso in the [[Channel 4]] production of ''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]'' (1992).\n\nHarris appeared in the rotating cast of the Off-Broadway staged reading of ''[[Wit & Wisdom]]''.<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/shows/wit-and-wisdom_20415/ \"Synopsis of Wit & Wisdom\"] at Theater Mania</ref> In 2007, she received the [[North Carolina Award]] for fine arts. Her husband, John Ehle, won the same award in 1972 for literature.<ref>[http://statelibrary.dcr.state.nc.us/ncawards/nca2.asp?bn=rhehle North Carolina Award profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815185943/http://statelibrary.dcr.state.nc.us/ncawards/nca2.asp?bn=rhehle |date=15 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, she appeared as [[Aunt May|Aunt May Parker]] in the [[Spider-Man (2002 film)|first film adaptation of ''Spider-Man'']], reprising the role in the sequels ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' (2004) and ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' (2007).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salfino |first1=Michael |title=Hold On, You\u2019re Spider-Man\u2019s Aunt May? |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spider-mans-aunt-may-has-never-looked-younger-1498667227 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=4 August 2018 |date=28 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Monahan |first1=Mark |title=The face is familiar: Rosemary Harris |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3670713/The-face-is-familiar-Rosemary-Harris.html |accessdate=4 August 2018 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2018, a week before her 91st birthday, Harris took over the role of Mrs Higgins in [[My Fair Lady#2018 Broadway revival|the Broadway revival of ''My Fair Lady'']] from [[Diana Rigg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/first-look-at-tony-winner-rosemary-harris-in-my-fair-lady-on-broadway|title=First Look at Tony Winner Rosemary Harris in My Fair Lady on Broadway|first=Hannah|last=Vine|date=28 September 2018|website=Playbill|accessdate=14 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085106/http://www.playbill.com/article/first-look-at-tony-winner-rosemary-harris-in-my-fair-lady-on-broadway|archive-date=16 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/news-features/rosemary-harris-returns-to-broadway-in-my-fair-lady-at-lincoln-center-theater|title=Rosemary Harris returns to Broadway in My Fair Lady at Lincoln Center Theater|website=New York Theater Guide|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1954\n|''[[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|Beau Brummell]]''\n|Mrs. Fitzherbert\n|film debut\n|-\n|1957\n|''[[The Shiralee (1957 film)|The Shiralee]]''\n|Lily Parker\n|\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Uncle Vanya (1963 film)